WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.180
All right, so we've been talking about security architecture and engineering and just to

00:17.180 --> 00:34.680
refocus. That means how we. All right, so we've been talking about security

00:34.680 --> 00:40.520
architecture and engineering and just to refocus. That means how we build

00:40.520 --> 00:45.400
architectures but also protect them by going through the engineering process

00:45.400 --> 00:50.080
itself which are the phases of how we need to involve security right from the

00:50.080 --> 00:54.760
start and throughout each of the phases. Now what can be really helpful from a

00:54.760 --> 00:59.080
security perspective is what we call models. Now before we get into what we

00:59.080 --> 01:03.000
call security models, we have to pause here and think about what the word

01:03.000 --> 01:08.040
model actually means because these are really useful in security. The word

01:08.040 --> 01:14.400
model is simply a representation of something. So if we have something that

01:14.400 --> 01:19.120
represents what the ultimate architecture needs to look like, it can be

01:19.120 --> 01:23.860
really helpful from a security perspective. So security models provide the

01:23.860 --> 01:29.320
rules by which we can build something that ultimately is going to be secure. So

01:29.320 --> 01:33.180
there are security models that exist out there that have been around for a

01:33.180 --> 01:38.520
very long time that can provide the rules by which we can implement security

01:38.520 --> 01:45.640
and ultimately have secure architectures that become importantly secured from

01:45.640 --> 01:50.920
a confidentiality perspective, from a integrity perspective. We typically don't

01:50.920 --> 01:56.760
need models to tell us how to achieve availability because availability is

01:56.760 --> 02:01.760
addressed through redundancy. We don't need rules to be able to understand what

02:01.760 --> 02:07.320
that is like. We simply build in cost-effective redundancy and we achieve

02:07.320 --> 02:12.840
availability. But there are rules by which we can achieve confidentiality and

02:12.840 --> 02:18.360
integrity. Those are referred to as security models. And some of these I'm sure

02:18.360 --> 02:25.280
you've heard of, Bellapagela, Biba, Clark Wilson, Brewer Nash are the major

02:25.280 --> 02:30.680
models that we need to focus on as far as the exam is concerned. Now what you

02:30.680 --> 02:35.560
need to remember is that there are really two types of models that only exist.

02:35.560 --> 02:42.920
Latest-based and rule-based. Only two types of models. Latest-based and rule-based.

02:42.920 --> 02:48.120
There are only two Latest-based models that we need to concern ourselves with.

02:48.120 --> 02:53.440
And the difference between them will be very apparent for you. But basically one

02:53.440 --> 03:00.000
addresses confidentiality only. The other one addresses integrity only. That's the

03:00.000 --> 03:04.720
difference between the two Latest-based models. So if you see questions on the

03:04.720 --> 03:10.760
exam that talk about what is the Latest-based model, then you know that the

03:10.760 --> 03:16.440
answer can only be one of two choices. Bellapagela only addresses confidentiality

03:16.440 --> 03:22.320
and Biba only addresses integrity. So first of all, let's look at what a

03:22.320 --> 03:27.600
Latest is. So if I say the word Latest, what comes to your mind? You may

03:27.600 --> 03:32.080
picture something that you see on your screen here as the slide. The best way to

03:32.080 --> 03:37.920
think of what a Latest-based model is is a layer-based model. So we've got

03:37.920 --> 03:43.600
different layers that provide different levels of security. So let's start, for

03:43.600 --> 03:49.240
example, with the first one, which is Bellapagela. The names of these models

03:49.240 --> 03:53.440
come from the people that came up with the rules in the first place. And this

03:53.440 --> 03:59.280
model actually dates back to the early 70s. But it was Bell and La Padilla that

03:59.280 --> 04:04.520
came up with the rules that we have to implement in order to address confidentiality.

04:04.520 --> 04:08.880
Now a lot of people think, why is it that we have to still think about these

04:08.880 --> 04:13.920
models, you know, decades later. Surely they've become obsolete. But the answer

04:13.920 --> 04:17.360
to that is something that all of us as security professionals should

04:17.360 --> 04:22.680
understand. And that is even though these models are very old, the fundamental

04:22.680 --> 04:28.360
concepts that they address and therefore the rules to achieve, for example,

04:28.360 --> 04:33.400
confidentiality are the same today as they were decades ago. And they will be

04:33.400 --> 04:38.400
the same decades from now. The fundamental rules and concepts are the same in

04:38.400 --> 04:43.360
how we dress confidentiality. Technology has changed, but the fundamental rules

04:43.360 --> 04:47.920
will never change. And so it's important for us to realize what those rules are

04:47.920 --> 04:53.200
that you need to implement in order to achieve confidentiality. So these two

04:53.200 --> 04:58.340
people thought, okay, if we want confidentiality to exist in any environment,

04:58.340 --> 05:03.340
what are the rules that need to exist? What are the rules that we need to enforce?

05:03.340 --> 05:08.700
And the first thing that they thought of is, okay, what happens in any architecture?

05:08.700 --> 05:15.700
There is always interaction between two entities. Those two entities are subjects

05:15.700 --> 05:20.340
and objects. I mean, when you look at any architecture, those are the two

05:20.340 --> 05:25.020
fundamental entities that will always interface with each other. And the

05:25.020 --> 05:30.020
difference between them, as we've learned before, is that subjects are always the

05:30.020 --> 05:35.140
active entity. The objects are going to be the passive entity. But if we want

05:35.140 --> 05:41.700
security to exist, we have to enforce rules between subjects and objects. So if you

05:41.700 --> 05:48.020
think of a lattice-based model, which is a layer-based model, this model only

05:48.020 --> 05:54.380
addresses confidentiality. So let's use a example. Let's say that we have three

05:54.380 --> 06:01.460
levels of confidentiality, high, medium, and low. And we have subjects, we have

06:01.460 --> 06:06.580
been placed in the medium layer. From a read perspective, what is it that

06:06.580 --> 06:11.780
subject should be able to do from a read perspective? So if we are in the

06:11.780 --> 06:17.580
medium layer, what can we read to enforce confidentiality and always have

06:17.580 --> 06:23.140
confidentiality requirements be addressed? Well, we can read anything that's in our

06:23.140 --> 06:29.020
layer. You can always do anything in our layer because that's the layer that

06:29.020 --> 06:35.100
we've been placed at. But we can also read anything that is below us. Because

06:35.100 --> 06:41.500
anything that is below us is less sensitive from a confidentiality perspective. So

06:41.500 --> 06:47.380
if you allow reading down, you are not breaking confidentiality requirements.

06:47.380 --> 06:53.580
However, we should not allow reading up because if we do, then you'd be

06:53.580 --> 06:58.940
allowing subjects to read sensitive information that they are not cleared for.

06:58.940 --> 07:05.060
That would break confidentiality. So the first rule of Bellapagela is actually

07:05.060 --> 07:11.820
if you have read capabilities, you can only read at your layer or down. Now

07:11.820 --> 07:17.420
what if we have right capabilities, right capabilities? Let's say we're in

07:17.420 --> 07:22.740
that medium layer. And so what is it that you can write to? Well, if you think

07:22.740 --> 07:26.540
about this from a confidentiality perspective, you can always do things that

07:26.540 --> 07:32.100
your own layer. So we can write to objects at our own layer, but to enforce

07:32.100 --> 07:37.580
confidentiality, what do we need to do? We need to allow either writing up or

07:37.580 --> 07:43.740
writing down to enforce confidentiality. However, you would allow writing up and

07:43.740 --> 07:50.220
not down. And here's why. If you allow writing down, we'd be taking knowledge

07:50.220 --> 07:56.220
that is available to us at the medium layer. And we'd be writing it down to a

07:56.220 --> 08:01.900
lower layer thereby disclosing confidential information to those people that are

08:01.900 --> 08:07.620
below us. That would break confidentiality. And therefore, writing down is not

08:07.620 --> 08:12.980
allowed. Writing up, however, is okay from a confidentiality perspective.

08:12.980 --> 08:18.940
Because those people above us can already read what exists in our own layer. So

08:18.940 --> 08:24.420
it's okay to take anything from our layer and write it up. That does not break

08:24.420 --> 08:30.300
confidentiality. So that's the second rule of the Bellapagela model. You can read

08:30.340 --> 08:36.660
at your layer or up, not down because that would break confidentiality. Now, the

08:36.660 --> 08:43.420
only last rule that exists here with Bellapagela is really combining both

08:43.420 --> 08:49.580
rules together. What if you have the ability to read and write? Well, based on the

08:49.580 --> 08:54.780
previous two rules, the only thing that you can do is read and write at your own

08:54.780 --> 09:00.180
layer. Nothing higher, nothing lower. And that's what we depict here as the last

09:00.340 --> 09:06.100
rule in the Bellapagela model. Now, one more thing to think about here before we move

09:06.100 --> 09:11.940
on to the next lattice-based model. But these guys, Bell and LaPagela, actually

09:11.940 --> 09:18.060
named each of these rules. The ability to be able to read is referred to as the

09:18.060 --> 09:23.940
simple security property. So if you see simple on the exam, it simply means the

09:23.940 --> 09:30.380
ability to read. The ability to write is referred to as the star property. So if you

09:30.380 --> 09:34.540
see star, it means the ability to write. And of course, we know that you can only

09:34.540 --> 09:41.140
write at your layer or higher. And the ability to read and write is referred to as the

09:41.140 --> 09:47.460
strong star property. So strong star means being able to read and write at the same

09:47.460 --> 09:55.940
time. Now, let's move on to the next lattice-based model, which of course is called Beba. Remember

09:55.940 --> 10:03.940
Bellapagela only addresses confidentiality. Beba only addresses integrity. All right, now

10:03.940 --> 10:09.620
the Beba model is something that only addresses integrity. This guy called Beba came along

10:09.620 --> 10:16.180
years after Bellapagela. Looked at the Bellapagela model and said, wow, this is a great model,

10:16.180 --> 10:22.980
but in my environment, Beba said, I'm only interested in integrity, not so much confidentiality.

10:22.980 --> 10:30.180
I'd like to have a model that is similar, but addresses integrity, not so much confidentiality.

10:30.180 --> 10:36.180
And so basically what he did is he took the Bellapagela model and adapted it to address

10:36.180 --> 10:41.980
integrity. Maybe he worked in a bank where something like integrity is very important.

10:41.980 --> 10:46.860
So what he did is he modified the rules to address integrity. Before we can understand

10:46.860 --> 10:52.540
this one, we have to just pause for a second and think about what integrity actually means

10:52.540 --> 10:57.020
from a security perspective. I think we've talked about this a few times, but integrity

10:57.020 --> 11:06.220
means meaningfulness, timeliness, currency, but accuracy is something that integrity really

11:06.220 --> 11:12.380
addresses. And if we think of integrity as addressing accuracy, it allows us to understand

11:12.380 --> 11:19.740
this model really easily. So instead of having three layers, let's say, of confidentiality,

11:19.740 --> 11:27.500
like Bellapagela addresses, this one addresses layers of integrity accuracy. So let's say we have

11:27.500 --> 11:33.500
three layers of accuracy, high, medium, and low. And just like before, we've been placed in

11:33.660 --> 11:40.540
the medium layer. Now, from a read perspective, what should we be able to read? Well, if you think

11:40.540 --> 11:47.420
about this, because we are reading layers of accuracy, it's going to be the opposite of Bellapagela.

11:47.420 --> 11:53.900
We should not be able to read anything that is lower than us. Because if you allow that,

11:53.900 --> 12:00.380
you are allowing people to read information that is less accurate. And so what you want is you

12:00.380 --> 12:08.540
want people to be able to read levels of higher accuracy, because reading higher accuracy information

12:08.540 --> 12:14.940
allows us to become more accurate, more knowledgeable, more current, more accurate in our knowledge.

12:14.940 --> 12:22.140
So in this case, we allow reading up, not down, because if you allow reading down, you'd be allowing

12:22.140 --> 12:28.220
people to read less accurate information. But if they can read up, they can read more accurate

12:28.220 --> 12:33.980
information, which obviously allows them to be more accurate in the decisions that they actually

12:33.980 --> 12:42.780
make. So the Bibel model is actually the opposite of Bellapagela. We do allow reading up and not

12:42.780 --> 12:50.540
down. And similarly, if you have right capabilities, what should you be able to write to? Well, you can

12:50.540 --> 12:55.500
write to your own layer, because you can always do things at your own layer. But in this case,

12:55.500 --> 13:02.220
we allow writing down, because you're taking information from our layer, which is more accurate

13:02.220 --> 13:09.820
than the layer below us. So by taking knowledge of information from our layer and writing it down

13:09.820 --> 13:17.260
to a lower layer, you are improving that layer with more accurate information, which is a goal of

13:17.260 --> 13:24.780
accuracy and integrity. So again, this is the opposite. We allow writing down, we should not allow

13:24.780 --> 13:30.940
writing up, because again, that layer is already more accurate. If we allowed writing up, you'd be

13:30.940 --> 13:38.940
contaminating that layer with less accurate information. So the second rule of Biba is you can write

13:38.940 --> 13:46.620
down, not up. And then the third rule is combining these together, right? That's called the strong

13:46.620 --> 13:52.940
star property as well, which means you can only do things at your own layer, nothing higher, nothing

13:53.660 --> 13:59.580
lower. Now, there is a third rule or a fourth rule, basically, that is called the invocation

13:59.580 --> 14:06.940
property. Invocation properly simply means that you cannot send information to someone that is

14:06.940 --> 14:13.740
rated at a higher layer of integrity than you are, because again, you'd be contaminating their

14:13.740 --> 14:20.220
knowledge with less accurate information. So it's almost like the ability to write rule that we

14:20.220 --> 14:27.100
just described. Now, what you need to remember about the Biba model as well is that he kept the same

14:27.100 --> 14:35.100
names that Belapagela came up with. In other words, simple star and strong star, but the difference

14:35.100 --> 14:42.300
here is the second word. This is going to help you on the exam. If you look for the second word

14:42.300 --> 14:49.180
after the words simple star and strong star, it's going to tell you whether the exam is talking about

14:49.180 --> 14:55.500
the Belapagela model or the Biba model. Because if the second word says integrity, for example,

14:55.500 --> 15:03.820
simple integrity property or the star integrity property or the strong star integrity property,

15:03.820 --> 15:09.580
then obviously they're talking about the Biba model. If it says anything else like the simple

15:09.580 --> 15:15.740
security property, then they're talking about the Belapagela model. That's how you distinguish

15:15.740 --> 15:24.300
between the two. So that essentially is the Biba model. Now, what if you're an organization

15:24.860 --> 15:33.900
where confidentiality and integrity are requirements like most organizations today? So you may want to

15:33.900 --> 15:41.260
implement both Belapagela and Biba. But if you look at the rules that they each enforce,

15:41.260 --> 15:47.020
you see that they're the opposite of each other. So if you implement both Belapagela and Biba,

15:47.020 --> 15:52.060
you'd have models that really cancel each other out, which would mean that nobody would have

15:52.060 --> 15:58.940
access to anything, which I suppose would be very secure, but not very practical. And so how do you

15:58.940 --> 16:05.340
implement both Belapagela and Biba together? Which obviously are requirements of most organizations

16:05.820 --> 16:12.460
today. Well, the way that you do it is called the Lippner implementation, named after this guy

16:12.460 --> 16:20.140
called Lippner, who was able to take both Belapagela and Biba and put them together. And it's not

16:20.140 --> 16:26.940
really considered to be a model on its own. The Lippner is referred to as a implementation

16:26.940 --> 16:33.660
and not a model, but he was able to take both Belapagela and Biba and put them together and

16:33.660 --> 16:40.060
actually make them work in an organization. It's called the Lippner implementation of both

16:40.060 --> 16:50.060
Belapagela and Biba.

